R Notebook for Gulfstream generated dataset

Overview of the dataset

We have two datasets which simulate the Sea Surface Height (SSH) and the Sea Surface Salinity (SSS) :

library(ncdf4)
library(lattice)

nc <- nc_open("ref.nc", write=FALSE, readunlim=TRUE, verbose=FALSE, 
        auto_GMT=TRUE, suppress_dimvals=FALSE )

print(nc)

NAT <- nc_open("NATL60.nc", write=FALSE, readunlim=TRUE, verbose=FALSE, 
              auto_GMT=TRUE, suppress_dimvals=FALSE )

We extract the two arrays which are interesting for us

ssh <- ncvar_get(nc,"ssh")
sss <- ncvar_get(NAT, "sss")

The values of the SSH and the SSS are contained in a large array. The size of the array is 201201365201201365. The dimensions 201201201201 stand for the spatial dimensions (respectively latitude and longitude) while 365365 symbolizes the time. The simulation is supposed to cover an entire year and a value of SSS and SSH is simulated for each day of the year. We can visualize the heatmap of the SSH for the first days.

levelplot(ssh[1:201,1:201,1],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(ssh[1:201,1:201,2],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(ssh[1:201,1:201,3],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

We can divide the space in three distinct zone, namely the upper, the central and the lower zone. Each zone correspond to different magnitude of SSH.

For given latitude and longitude, we also plot the annual variation of the SSH :

lon<-150
lat<-20
plot(1:365, ssh[lon,lat,1:365], "line", xlab = "time", ylab="ssh")

We have to be careful that the day 1 is not the 1st1st January but the 1st1st October. For consistency we should divide the year within different periods (winter, summer ).

We are particularly interesting in the way the time derivatives of the ssh behave. Noting XtXt the value of ssh at day We use the following approximation for the time gradient and laplacian derivative of the ssh :

t=Xt+1Xtt=Xt+12Xt+Xt1t=Xt+1Xtt=Xt+12Xt+Xt1

We create the corresponding dataset :

gradssh <- array( dim = c(201,201,364))

for (i in 1:364){
  gradssh[,,i] <- ssh[,,i+1]-ssh[,,i]
}

lapssh <- array( dim = c(201,201,363))


for (i in 2:364){
  lapssh[,,i-1]<-ssh[,,i-1]+ssh[,,i+1]-2*ssh[,,i]
}

Were now able to plot the gradient of the ssh for the first three days :

levelplot(gradssh[1:201,1:201,1],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(gradssh[1:201,1:201,2],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(gradssh[1:201,1:201,3],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

We can also plot the time variation of the gradient for a given location :

plot(1:364,gradssh[lon,lat,1:364],"line", xlab = "time", ylab="ssh gradient")

Modelling with GPD-Elliptical laws

A random variable XX of RnRn is GPD-elliptical if its density is of the following type

f(x)=cng,((x)1(x))f(x)=cng,((x)1(x))

with a definite positive matrix of MnnMnn, a vector of RnRn, c a normalising constant and g,g, a real-valued function of the form

g,(s)=((1+s)+)1>0<2ng,(s)=((1+s)+)1>0<2n
where f+f+ denotes the positive part of ff. We usually write

Xn(,,g,)Xn(,,g,)

It could also be reformulated in the following manner :

X=+RAUX=+RAU
with AMnnAMnn such that AA=AA=, URnURn uniformly distributed on the sphere unit and RR+RR+, called the radial variable, independent from UU with density :

h(r)=20tn21g,(t)dtrn1g,(r2)I[0,[(r)h(r)=20tn21g,(t)dtrn1g,(r2)I[0,[(r)

In the univariate case, n=1n=1 and R+R+ and A=12A=12. We focus on the univariate case when RRs support is bounded. It is equivalent to consider negative values for . If <0<0, RRs support is [0,][0,]. The upper bound will be written xFxF. Its cumulative distribution function,HH, is :

H(r)=B(r2x2F ; 12,11)H(r)=B(r2xF2 ; 12,11)
where B stands for the incomplete Beta function.

We wish to get insight in the extreme behavior of GPD-elliptical variables.In particular we will pay specific attention to the behavior of |X||X|.

For a given real-valued YY, we will write that YU(xF,)YU(xF,)if its cumulative distribution function have the form of HH with parameters \xF\xF and . We can easily check that if YU(xF,)YU(xF,) and R+R+, then YU(xF,)YU(xF,).For any univariate GPD-elliptical random variable X, |X||X| belongs to the family of UU. and xFxF have different impact on the extreme for a UU variable.

stands for the frequency of apparition of extreme events.For a given xFxF

U(xF,)U[0,xF]0U(xF,)0U(xF,)U[0,xF]0U(xF,)0
xFxF is the upper bound of the distribution and could be viewed as the intensity of extremes.

Examples

Let Xn(,,g,)Xn(,,g,), X=(X1,X2,...,Xn)X=(X1,X2,...,Xn). As mentioned previously, we denote xF=xF=. We seek to characterize the differences in terms of extremes between the marginals XiXi and a given linear of the XiXi of the form :

Y=WX , WMn1(R)Y=WX , WMn1(R)
We keep focusing on the centered distribution, it is equivalent to set to 00 without loss of generality. The marginals are then defined by :

|Xi|U(xFi , ~)xFi=(i,i)12xF~=1,=n12|Xi|U(xFi , ~)xFi=(i,i)12xF~=1,=n12

The linear combination of the XiXi is defined by :

$$ |Y|U(x_{F_Y} , )\ x_{F_Y} = (WW)^{}x_F

$$ The parameter ~~ is the same for the marginals and the linear combination. The frequency of extremes behaves identically.The intensity of extremes is modified.

Case of a ponderated sum

Suppose YY is a ponderated sum of XiXi, and the XiXi iid. In this case, =aIn=aIn with aR+aR+. Because YY is a ponderated sum of XiXi, WWs elements are positive and sum to 1. We can easily infer that xFY=WWxFixFY=WWxFi and thus xFYxFixFYxFi. The upper bound is reduced.

#First attempt to model the gradient

We assume that, for a given location, the gradient have an univariate GPD-elliptical distribution.We plot hereafter the experimental cdf of the absolute value of the centered gradient

# Fonction de rpartition empirique

Femp<-function(vect,x){
  l=length(vect)
  return(sum(vect<x)/l)
}


Fempgrad<-(0:100)
for (i in 1:101){
  Fempgrad[i]<-Femp(abs(gradssh[lon,lat,1:364]-mean(gradssh[lon,lat,1:364])),((i-1)*0.0008))
}

plot(0.0008*(0:100),Fempgrad,"line", xlab="Gradient of SSH", ylab="Empiric cdf")
## Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): le type de graphe 'line' sera tronqu au
## premier caractre

A first idea is to hand-tuned the value of and \xF\xF to fit the empiric cdf.

#cdf of univariate GPD-elliptical value

ksin<--0.015
xf<-0.07

H<-function(r){
  return(pbeta((r/xf)**2, 1/2,-1/ksin+1))
}

#Initialization of the parameters

xfmin<-xf
E<-sum((H((0:100)*0.0008)-Fempgrad)**2) #mean-square error
ksinmin<-ksin
k<-0

#Loop to refine the parameters

while (k<200){
  xfboucle<-xf
  for (b in 0:200){
    xf<-(xfboucle-0.01+b*0.0001)
    Enew<-sum((H((0:100)*0.0008)-Fempgrad)**2)
    if (Enew<E){
      xfmin<-xf
      E<-Enew
    }
  }
  xf<-xfmin
  for (j in 0.001*(1:1000)){
    ksin<--j
    Enew<-sum((H((0:100)*0.0008)-Fempgrad)**2)
    if (Enew<E){
      ksinmin<-ksin
      E<-Enew
    }
  }
  ksin<-ksinmin
  k<-k+1
}
  print(E)
## [1] 0.03064377
  print(xf)
## [1] 0.0798
  print(ksin)
## [1] -0.058

We can visualize the cdf found using this technique (in red), and compare it with the experimental cdf (in green):

plot(0.0008*(0:100),H((0:100)*0.0008),"line",col="red",xlab="Gradient of SSH", ylab="cdf")

A major disadvantage is the high dependency between the initial condition and the convergence of the algorithm.
